## Getting Started

### Client Setup

1. **Navigate to the client folder:**
   ```bash
   cd client
Install dependencies:

bash
Copy
npm install
Server Setup
Navigate to the server folder:

bash
Copy
cd server
Install dependencies:

bash
Copy
npm install
Set Up Environment Variables:

Create a .env file in the server folder with the following variables:

ini
Copy
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=<your MongoDB connection string>
JWT_SECRET=<your secret key>
Running the Application
Client
Start the Development Server:

bash
Copy
npm start
The client runs on http://localhost:3000.

A proxy is configured in package.json to forward API requests to the backend on port 5000.

Server
Start in Development Mode:

bash
Copy
npm run dev
For Production:

Build the server:

bash
Copy
npm run build
Start the server:

bash
Copy
npm start
The server listens on the port defined in your .env file (default is 5000).

Automated Testing
Backend tests are set up using Jest and Supertest.

To run tests in the server folder:

bash
Copy
npm run test
Tests are located in server/src/tests and cover authentication and data routes.

Ensure MongoDB is accessible during testing, and note that tests include cleanup to close connections.

Continuous Integration (CI)
A GitHub Actions workflow is configured to run linting and tests automatically.

Workflow Location:
.github/workflows/ci.yml

Trigger:
On pushes and pull requests to main or feature branches.

Environment Variables
The server requires the following environment variables (set in the .env file):

PORT: Port for the server (e.g., 5000)

MONGO_URI: MongoDB connection string

JWT_SECRET: Secret key for signing JWT tokens

Deployment
Consider the following for deployment:

Docker: Create Dockerfiles for both client and server.

Staging & Production Environments: Automate deployment via CI/CD pipelines.

Environment Management: Securely manage your environment variables and secrets.

Future Enhancements
Client-side Testing: Add tests for React components using Jest and React Testing Library.

Advanced Authentication: Implement auto-logout, token refresh, and a global auth context.

API Documentation: Use Swagger to document backend endpoints.

Performance Improvements: Code-splitting and lazy loading on the client; caching strategies on the server.

